<handout xml:id="sec-1-1-systems">
  <title>Section 1.1: Systems of Linear Equations</title>

  <page>
    <title>Topics and Objectives</title>
    <p><em>Topics</em></p>
    <ulist>
      <item>Systems of Linear Equations</item>
      <item>Matrix Notation</item>
      <item>Elementary Row Operations</item>
      <item>Existence and Uniqueness of Solutions</item>
    </ulist>

    <p><em>Goals</em></p>
    <olist>
      <item>Characterize a linear system by the number of solutions and consistency.</item>
      <item>Apply elementary row operations to solve linear systems.</item>
      <item>Express a system as an augmented matrix.</item>
    </olist>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>A Single Linear Equation</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-single-linear-equation">
      <title>Linear equation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>A <em>linear equation</em> has the form</p>
        <me>a_1 x_1 + a_2 x_2 + \cdots + a_n x_n = b,</me>
        <p>where <m>a_1,\dots,a_n</m> and <m>b</m> are the <em>coefficients</em>, <m>x_1,\dots,x_n</m> are the <em>variables</em> (unknowns), and <m>n</m> is the <em>dimension</em> (number of variables).</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><strong>Examples.</strong></p>
    <ulist>
      <item><m>2x_1 + 4x_2 = 4</m> describes a line in two dimensions.</item>
      <item><m>3x_1 + 2x_2 + x_3 = 6</m> describes a plane in three dimensions.</item>
    </ulist>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Systems of Linear Equations</title>

    <p>When we have more than one linear equation, we have a <em>system of linear equations</em>. For example:</p>
    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      x_1 \;+\; 1.5\,x_2 \;+\; \pi x_3 \;=\; 4 \\
      5x_1 \;+\; \phantom{1.5\,x_2} \;+\; 7x_3 \;=\; 5
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <definition xml:id="def-solution-set">
      <title>Solution to a linear system</title>
      <statement>
        <p>The set of all values of <m>x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n</m> that satisfy <em>every</em> equation in the system is the <em>solution set</em>.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><linebreak/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-guess-a-solution">
      <title>Guessing a solution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Verify that <m>(x_1,x_2,x_3)=(1,2,0)</m> is a solution to the system above.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Substitute: <m>1 + 1.5\cdot 2 + \pi\cdot 0 = 1 + 3 = 4</m> (first equation) and <m>5\cdot 1 + 7\cdot 0 = 5</m> (second equation). Both hold, so <m>(1,2,0)</m> is a solution. Because there are two equations in three variables, there are typically infinitely many solutions (a one-parameter family).</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Two-Dimensional Case</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-2d-how-many">
      <title>How many solutions?</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider each system and determine how many solutions it has.</p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
          x_1 - 2x_2 \;=&\; -1 \\[-2pt]
          -x_1 + 3x_2 \;=&\; 3
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
          x_1 - 2x_2 \;=&\; -1 \\[-2pt]
          -x_1 + 2x_2 \;=&\; 3
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
          x_1 - 2x_2 \;=&\; -1 \\[-2pt]
          -x_1 + 2x_2 \;=&\; 1
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          (i) Adding the two equations gives <m>x_2=2</m>, then <m>x_1=3</m>, so there is a <em>unique</em> solution <m>(3,2)</m>.
          (ii) Adding yields <m>0=2</m>, so the system is <em>inconsistent</em> (no solution).
          (iii) Adding yields <m>0=0</m>; the equations are dependent, giving <em>infinitely many</em> solutions, e.g., <m>x_2=t</m>, <m>x_1=-1+2t</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> A system of linear equations in two variables can have <em>zero</em>, <em>one</em>, or <em>infinitely many</em> solutions.</p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Three-Dimensional Case</title>

    <p>A linear equation in three variables, <m>a_1x_1 + a_2x_2 + a_3x_3 = b</m>, defines a plane in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-3d-two-eq">
      <title>Two equations in three variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>How many solutions can a system of <em>two</em> linear equations in three variables have?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The solution set can be empty (parallel, distinct planes), a line (typical case), or a plane (if the equations are the same plane).</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-3d-three-eq">
      <title>Three equations in three variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>How many solutions can a system of <em>three</em> linear equations in three variables have?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The system can have no solution, exactly one solution (a point), or infinitely many solutions (e.g., a line or a plane) depending on consistency and rank.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Every linear system has either <em>zero</em>, <em>one</em>, or <em>infinitely many</em> solutions.</p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Row Reduction by Elementary Row Operations</title>

    <p>One way to solve a system is by graphing, but this is impractical for larger systems. A more useful approach is to manipulate the equations using <em>row operations</em>:</p>
    <olist>
      <item><em>Replacement/Addition</em>: add a multiple of one row to another.</item>
      <item><em>Interchange</em>: swap two rows.</item>
      <item><em>Scaling</em>: multiply a row by a nonzero scalar.</item>
    </olist>

    <example xml:id="ex-row-reduction">
      <title>Row-reducing a 3Ã—3 system</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Apply row operations to simplify the system and identify the solution(s):</p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
          x_1 - 2x_2 + x_3 &= 0 \\
          2x_2 - 8x_3 &= 8 \\
          5x_1 \phantom{- 2x_2}\; - 5x_3 &= 10
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Augmented matrix: <m>\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -8 \amp 8 \\ 5 \amp 0 \amp -5 \amp 10 \end{array}\right]</m>.</p>
        <p>Perform <m>R_3 \leftarrow R_3 - 5R_1</m> to get <m>\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp -8 \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 10 \amp -10 \amp 10 \end{array}\right]</m>. Then scale: <m>R_2 \leftarrow \tfrac{1}{2}R_2</m>, <m>R_3 \leftarrow \tfrac{1}{10}R_3</m>, giving <m>\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]</m>.</p>
        <p>Next, <m>R_3 \leftarrow R_3 - R_2</m> gives <m>\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp -3 \end{array}\right]</m>, so <m>x_3 = -1</m>, <m>x_2 - 4(-1) = 4</m> yields <m>x_2 = 0</m>, and <m>x_1 - 2(0) + (-1) = 0</m> gives <m>x_1 = 1</m>. Thus the unique solution is <m>(x_1,x_2,x_3) = (1,0,-1)</m>; the system is <em>consistent</em>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Augmented Matrices</title>
    <p>It is redundant to write variables repeatedly, so we use an <em>augmented matrix</em>. For the previous system, the augmented matrix is</p>
    <me>
      \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 2 \amp -8 \amp 8 \\
      5 \amp 0 \amp -5 \amp 10
      \end{array}\right],
    </me>
    <p>where the vertical bar separates the coefficient matrix (for <m>x_1,x_2,x_3</m>) from the constants.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-consistency-check">
      <title>Determine consistency</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Determine whether the following system has a solution.</p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}
          &\;\;\; x_2 - 4x_3 &=&\; 8 \\
          2x_1 - 3x_2 + 2x_3 &=&\; 1 \\
          4x_1 - 8x_2 + 12x_3 &=&\; 1
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Augmented matrix: <m>\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 0 \amp 1 \amp -4 \amp 8 \\ 2 \amp -3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp -8 \amp 12 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]</m>. Swap rows to get a pivot in the first column, then eliminate: <m>R_3 \leftarrow R_3 - 2R_1</m> (with the current <m>R_1</m> as <m>[2\, -3\, 2\, |\, 1]</m>) gives <m>[0\, -2\, 8\, |\, -1]</m>. Using <m>R_2=[0\,1\,-4\,|\,8]</m>, perform <m>R_3 \leftarrow R_3 + 2R_2</m> to obtain <m>[0\,0\,0\,|\,15]</m>, which is impossible. Therefore the system is <em>inconsistent</em> and has <em>no solution</em>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Consistent Systems and Row Equivalence</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-consistent">
      <title>Consistent system</title>
      <statement>
        <p>A linear system is <em>consistent</em> if it has at least one solution. Otherwise, it is <em>inconsistent</em>.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-row-equivalence">
      <title>Row equivalence</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Two matrices are <em>row equivalent</em> if a sequence of row operations transforms one matrix into the other.</p>
        <p><em>Note:</em> If the augmented matrices of two linear systems are row equivalent, they have the same solution set.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><strong>Fundamental questions.</strong> (i) Does a given linear system have a solution (is it consistent)? (ii) If it is consistent, is the solution unique?</p>
  </page>
</handout>
